st, Gerhard, Hartmut, Heinz.","German: from the German personal name <i>Karl</i>, from Old High German <i>karl</i> ‘man, husband, freeman’. The popularity of this name and its cognates in central and northern Europe was greatly enhanced by its status as a royal and imperial name; in particular it was bestowed in honor of the Frankish emperor Charlemagne (about 742–814; Latin name <i>Carolus Magnus</i>). This surname is also found in some other European countries, e.g. in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Croatia, but is relatively rare there. See also   Carl   and   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"den","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄧, see   Deng  .","Chinese: possibly from the Romanization of certain Chinese personal names of some early Chinese immigrants in the US.","Origin undetermined. — Note: It is possible that in the population figure published by the US Census Bureau the Dutch case-inflected definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, which forms first part of surnames such as   Den Bleyker   and   Den Boer  , is in some instances counted as an independent surname. Compare   Ten  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deng","meanings":["‘Eternal’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Kung Sverker den yngre Karlsson was born about 1164, his father, Karl VON SCHWEDEN, was 36 and his mother, Christine Stigsdotter Hvide, was 25. He married Benedikta Ebbesdotter Hvide about 1180. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died about 17 July 1210, in Västergötland, Sweden, at the age of 47."},"et":{"Abt 1164–about 17 July 1210":"umbes 1164–umbes 17. juuli 1210","1164–1210":"1164–1210","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1180–1251":"1180–1251","1185–1248":"1185–1248","1192–1232":"1192–1232","–1198":"–1198","1130–1167":"1130–1167","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","after 1180":"pärast 1180","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1198":"1198","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1130":"1130","